# Coding conventions

## Structure

- `lib.rs` is module declarations and `pub use` re-exports only. No logic ever goes there.
- All public operations are methods on `Context`. If a user needs to import a type from `keys` or `ciphertext` directly, re-export it from `lib.rs` instead.
- `scratch` is a `pub mod`, but every item in `scratch.rs` is `pub(crate)` — treat it as internal; it is not re-exported from `lib.rs` and is not part of the supported API.

## Types

- The backend is selected at compile time via `crate::backend::BE` (see `src/backend.rs`). `type Mod = Module<crate::backend::BE>` in `context.rs`. Do not add `<BE: Backend>` generics to any public type. Use `crate::backend::BE` everywhere internally instead of hard-coding `FFT64Ref`.
- Layout fields on `Params` and its nested structs use Poulpy newtypes (`Degree`, `Base2K`, etc.). Prefer `Params::unsecure()` for the Poulpy `bdd_arithmetic` example bundle (not a security claim). For a custom `Params`, keep all layouts self-consistent (same `n_glwe`, `base2k`, `rank`, … across `glwe_layout`, `ggsw_layout`, `bdd_layout`).
- `Ciphertext<T>` is always in standard (`Vec<u8>`) form. `FheUintPrepared` must never escape `eval_binary`.

## Error handling

Poulpy panics on parameter mismatches and scratch underflow — those are programming errors, not runtime failures. squid follows the same convention. No `Result` wrappers around operations that Poulpy asserts on.

## Naming

Stay close to Poulpy's vocabulary when naming wrapper types so users who read Poulpy docs can map concepts across (e.g. `EvaluationKey` maps to `BDDKey`, `SecretKey` maps to `GLWESecret + LWESecret`).
